description.text:
This fidget spinner was intended to meet the "fidget" needs of students with ADHD and autism. By unevenly weighting the arms of the spinner, it provides additional sensory stimulation that, hopefully, will help the student focus on the instruction and be less of a distraction than a standard spinner.

The spinner uses a standard 608ZZ 8x22x7 skate bearing available here:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00NX1WBA0/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

It also uses up to six 8mm chrome ball bearings available here:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B008M3584K/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

It helps to sand the outer and inner surfaces of the skate bearing before super-gluing the skate bearing into the spinner and the two caps into the skate bearing. Note that the 3D Printing Nerd has an interesting proposal for how to mate the two caps without needing glue in this video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EgOuvOLiwAM

Students modeled the caps using Tinkercad (this was part of a lesson in 3D printing and modeling) and then chose the colors for their spinner, each cap, and number of ball bearings for their own custom spinner. They could even choose the color of the plug that substituted for a ball bearing but most chose to match the spinner color. The PDF file contains the dimensions of the caps.

See this page for a description of how the spinner can be used in an experiment that teaches about conservation of angular momentum:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2338377

<iframe allowfullscreen="None" frameborder="0" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/G7EhxgYU1Bs" ></iframe>

This spinner was designed in Fusion 360 (*.f3d files are included) as part of a lesson on 3D printing. The students modeled the skate bearing caps in Tinkercad as three cylinders all resting on the workplane. Additionally, two boxes were used to cut an "x" on the outside to help keep the spinner from slipping out of the student's hands and to accommodate additional components for a lesson on conservation of angular momentum (see the "Spinner Science" thing). See the PDF file for cap dimensions. The inner cylinder is not perfectly round and that makes it easier to insert into the skate bearing and still provides a reasonable grip.

I wanted an all in one Stratux so I didn't have drag a USB power brick around if I didn't want too. (Plus it's just another thing I get to randomly forget)

This case has ample room for a single cell LiPo. I happened to have one of these packs that had a bad cell so I disassembled it and used one of the 3 good cells. This was almost a perfect fit.

Inside you have 130x42x10mm worth of space under the Pi. I placed some thin foam between the Pi and the pack just to keep the sharp pins out of the LiPo pack.

You'll also need:
1 x Charger/Booster
1 x Switch

The switch can be wired to automatically shutdown the booster when the Lipo gets below 3.2v by connecting the switch to the following pads on the PowerBoost 1000c. Make sure the EN is connected to the center pin of the switch:

GND | EN | LBO

For printing I recommend ABS, PETG or another material that does well in close proximity to heat. Both the booster and the SDRs can get quite warm in operation.

This is my modification of the awesome PKE Meter by hobbyman.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xTfZLYqommg

My changes were done to accommodate the electronics and to simplify the design for my 7 year old son. I scaled the whole model up to 110%, added a screen holder for a 0.96" Inch LCD LED Module 128X64. I removed the top three buttons and designed it around a 2 button input method for a kid. I also modified the battery area to accommodate the 4 AAA's to power all of this since it was scaled up and the area was too big now.

No buttons pressed it is in the idle state. When button one is pressed and held it is at 50% and button two at 100%. This has worked very well for my son.

The electronics are based off an arduino nano with a custom PCB fabricated by OshPark. You can find the arduino code, pcb schematic, and brd files in my github repo here:

https://github.com/CountDeMonet/Arduino_PKE_Meter

The full parts list:

  • Arduino nano clone
  • Buck converter to power the servo at 5v
  • Diymall 0.96" Inch Yellow Blue I2c IIC Serial Oled LCD LED Module
  • A micro servo of your choosing. I used a bluebird that I had laying around
  • Cheaper to get the rest in a starter kit from amazon. I used:
    -- 2 buttons
    -- 7 220ohm resistors
    -- a buzzer
  • 14 3mm Yellow LED's I bought a ton of led's a while back for other projects.
  • one on/off switch I ripped out of one of my sons dead toys

I printed mine at .3mm resolution with a 20% infill with supports. This print requires a lot of supports but it is worth it. I wish I would have printed at .2mm resolution but my prototype has become the one my son will use.

I have included the buttons_filled.3mf file in case you need to adjust the spacing for the buttons. I built my own input board for two standard buttons from an arduino kit. If you choose something else you can modify this file to work with it.

Update 8/18/2017
I needed a belt holder for the meter so I modified the one daniel_nelms made to fit this one and reduced it in size a bit.

The hotbed wires on the Tronxy P802 are not secured with anything other than the solder joints. As a result they are subject to failure from stress. Eventually they will have to be re-soldered. This is an attempt to rectify that situation. My original wires were beginning to fray, so I replaced them with the longer 14ga wire that is required for this mod. The cable chain itself is from this post:https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:34661. The frame mount is a heavily modified version of another design which I found here, but have been unable to find since. I printed out the original, took measurements, & used Sketchup to redraw it to suit my needs. I only retained the original ramped design of the connector & the hole location. The frame mount & the horizontal chase are interlocked using a dovetail & secured by the original screw. The frame mount is captured by the Z axis motor mount. The outer end of the horizontal chase is secured by a clip. The Sketchup files are included, so it can be modified to suit your needs.

The bed must be rotated 90 degrees from the original position.
The bed end should be printed with PETG or ABS. All other parts can be printed with PLA.
The bed end is designed to be attached with 4 x 16 SS socket head capscrews that replace the original M4 screws.
You MUST replace your original heated bed wires with longer 14Ga. wire. The original wires are too short.
Print the frame mount in the upright position.

description.text:
A simple hanging mount designed to accommodate most types of filament spools and be printed with little to no support material. The octagon-shaped crossbar which supports the spool allows the guide arm to be oriented at 45 degree angles. Included in the file is a small clip which affixes to the guide arm. You may need to give it a little extra attention with a file or sandpaper to achieve a proper fit, depending on how well calibrated your machine is. The chains shown supporting my spools were part of another project from earlier that day, but adapted well to this design. Should you wish to use them yourself, I've included the file for a single link of the chain. Copy, paste, print, and enjoy! Revision 1
  • The new filament guide arm is ~9.5mm further from the spool axis than the original, and is slightly smaller.
  • The modular filament clip has been adjusted to fit the redesigned guide arm.
  • The filament guide hole has been rotated by 90 degrees from the original, and the inner taper has been shallowed out considerably. This was done to reduce flexion stress when feeding out larger diameter spools.
  • Crossbar end caps have been thickened for strength. This has expanded the Y axis by ~2.5mm.
    • I kept the original version (with slightly modified end caps) in the files for those who either preferred that design or have smaller print surfaces which are simply incapable of handling Rev.1

I modified the dimensions to use 3mm Acrylic so it could be cheaper and faster to cut. I wanted to modify it so people could use hacker spaces and places like techshop laser cutters. Even at 40W you can still cut this in a single pass.  
If you don't have access to a laser cutter let me know and we can work something out.

Revision E adjusted some spacing issues people noticed in the google group. I made the tube openings in the back a little wider and taller and corrected the hole spacing on the front panel. They were off by .5 mm.   
It was suggested to use 10mm bolts for the hood instead of 12mm bolts by Shawn in the makerbot google group. I have updated the parts list below to reflect this. Thanks Shawn!  
I recently updated the files to move the bolt hole for the right side panel to the top center instead of the sides. A few people noticed that on full size prints that the Y axis was hitting the bolt on the right side. If you have/made the older version you can remove the front bolt. It's plenty stable without it. This looks to be a problem with the orginal files so no matter what thickness you make you will need to move the holes.  
I shorten up and modified the parts list to make it easier and included McMaster part #. Please note that I list how many pieces you need but the smallest packs are usually around 50 so you will have plenty of spares.  
2 - M3 22mm Bolts (McMaster #91292A801 50 pack)  
7 - M4 12mm Bolts (McMaster #90116A209 50 pack)  
15 - #8 Washers (McMaster #90126A512 100 pack)  
7 - M4 Nuts (McMaster #94150A335 50 pack)  
15 - M3 10mm Bolts (McMaster #91290A115 100 pack)  
15 - M3 Nuts (McMaster #98676A100 100 pack)

Step #1     Bolt the hood together with 12mm M3 bolts and set it on top. No Fasteners needed to hold it in place.  
Step #2     Use the 12mm M4 bolts and washers to pinch fit the side panels on.  
Step #3     Replace the 2 top front nuts/bolts with the 22mm M3 bolts to make a hanger to hold the front door on.

description.text:
This is a two pieces (per corner) 6mm standoff with a selection of mating glass clamps. The 6mm gap is to add insulation.
I have 1.3 mm glass which is a little narrow so I have wider clamps for it.
I have added clamps for 3mm as well.
This design is for long glass (picture frame glass). If the glass was the right size you might do it differently.
The SU has a few other parts I was playing with - single piece holders that didn't really work.

3D Printed, tested and in use.
I suggest printing in ABS not PLA because it will get hot.
Obviously overtighening may break your glass.
I intend to replace my Y-bar-ends with tapped versions so there is no nut to rattle off if the screw is loose.
Hint - under the standoff is a good place to pack up for minor bed leveling.
PS. I've added a nut replacement thing. I tap these to M3 but not all the way so the screw remains a little tight. I use them instead of nuts for the back mounts. The ridge goes up the side of the wooden bed to stop them rotating.

title: Ooznest OX CNC Machine (3D Printed ABS/PETG Parts)

description.text:
This remix is simply providing all of the aluminium plates as STL files for 3D printing, rather than having to buy or mill the aluminium parts. I've 'tuned' the parts to provide as much rigidity as possible whilst still maintaining dimensional accuracy by recessing the screw holes to the original depth. The original project and documentation can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1684109

This CNC machine looks to be the most stable I can find on Thingiverse and OpenBuilds. It's got some very detailed supporting documentation. Someone else has built it by printing the parts in ABS and has reportedly had decent results: http://www.openbuilds.com/builds/ooznest-ox-with-3d-printed-gantry-plates.4478/

Their recommendation was to extrude the 3mm aluminium parts at 6mm in ABS so I've taken it a little further and made all parts 8mm thick to ensure they're strong and rigid enough. I haven't build this yet, so I'm not sure if making these parts 8mm thick will affect dimensional accuracy during the build. I'm just sharing the extruded DXF files for anyone who's looking for them.

Note: the _Xx denotes how many of this part you'll need to print. eg. Y-BRACE_X2.stl means you need to print 2 of these parts.

Edit 24/05/2017: Based on advice from the OpenBuild forums, I've made the plates thicker at 10mm and recessed the screw holes to a 6mm thickness.

If you are using the Filastruder + FilaWinder combo and extruding 3mm filament, then you will quickly realize how difficult it is for the servo motor (which controls the filament guide) to guide the filament from the left of the spool to the right, because of how stiff 3mm filament is, as opposed to 1.75mm. This puts a lot of stress on the motor and it eventually stops moving the filament guide, and all the filament gets bunched up in the middle of the spool.  
This base extension fixes this problem by increasing the distance from the filament guide to the PTFE tube, thus making it far easier for the servo motor to move the filament guide its entire course.

Print with at least 40% infill. PLA or ABS. 3 perimeters.
Because of the added length to the base and the heavy force of the motor creating a lot of pull on the filament through the PTFE tube, this causes the extension to bend quite a bit. So a 4mm hole is placed near the bottom of the extension, allowing you to screw it into the wall (or if you have a horizontal setup, into whatever material you have it sitting on). You can make the hole slightly bigger if needed.

description.text:
This is a design I came up with to integrate a Z axis brace and enclosure frame into the one bolt up mod. The frame is designed to take a 3mm PMMA half enclosure for the front of the printer to help stabilise temperatures for ABS printing. The rear half will be up in the next few weeks along with the enclosure specs.

The frame is meant to separate the hot print area from the electronics case.

The STL files are for one side only and will need to be mirrored and printed a second time. The front brackets and horizontal cross braces can be printed as a pair on a 200x200 print bed.

Printer:

Cocoon Create Touch (Wahao i3 Plus Clone)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

35%, 1.2mm wall

Notes:

Parts list
16x (M3x10mm) bolts
16x M3 washers
2x (M5x15mm) hex key bolts
2x M5 wide face washers
24x M4 washers
8x (M4x16mm) hex key bolts
4x M4 nuts
2x ~415mm M4 thread rod (confirm measurement on printer)
2x ~380mm, 10mm OD, 1mm wall aluminium tube (confirm measurement on printer)
2x 300mm x 7mm OD /4mm ID rigid poly sprinkler riser

Instructions
-The 2x M5 bolts and wide washers are used used to bolt the lower front brackets on
-8x M4 bolts and 16x M4 washers used to bolt horizontal cross brace between the front bracket and the lower z axis brace. Use washers under each bolt head and nut to help spread the loads
-16x M3 washers and M3 bolts used to bolt Z axis brackets on. I used phillips heads here to limit the torque that can be applied through the plastic mounts.
-4x M4 nuts, 2x M4 threaded rods, 8x M3 washers and 2x aluminium tubes used for bracing.

  1. The threaded rod should go betwen and through the upper and lower braces. One M4 nut on each outer side, using a washer under each nut
  2. Use a washer on each end of the aluminium tube to stop the tube walls from cutting into the plastic mounts

From bottom up, the order of construction for each brace is:
nut > washer > lower printed mount > washer > slide sprinkler hose onto threaded rod > slide aluminium tube over rod > washer > upper Z axis mount > washer > nut

The top bracket is a bit tight, so use small needle nose pliers to help position the top washer and nut on the Z axis braces. Tightern up on from the bottom of the front braces.

Notes
-The M4 rod is designed to act in tension while the aluminium tube is in compression. This design needs both to work. Pre-drill the M4 holes with a 4mm drill and M3 holes with 3mm drill bits to help rods and bolts insert.
-The slot for each front panel foot sags a bit during printing unless you use a bit of support material. Its only minor and can be cleaned up with a craft knife or sharp scraper.

A little sanding might be necessary depending on the tolerances of your printer.

I wanted to be able to run Lipo batteries in my RC18T, so I designed this battery boy that mounts to the posts intended for the battery hold down strap. Now I can run these lipos.

Heavy-Duty Air-Tight Filament Spool Case

Having used a fair few spools of moisture sensitive materials over the years I am getting a little bored of constantly drying the same filament spool again and again. The Heavy-Duty Air-Tight Filament Spool Case is designed to enclose a single standard 200mm spool in an air-tight enclosure.

The standard design allows for 65mm wide spools with a 50mm centre. You can alter this by adding or removing layers and editing the spool base.f3d file. Remember to adjust the screw lengths if you do make changes. Designed for 1.75mm filament. Adjust in Fusion 360 if you would like to use 2.85mm filament instead.

You will need access to a laser cutter. I have laid-up all the parts, excluding the two caps, to fit onto a single 900mm x 600mm sheet. The design uses 5mm Cast Acrylic Sheet but you can use just about any thickness you like, just remember to recount the number of components you'll need. The Cork Seal is made from 2mm Cork Sheet.

I highly recommend making the laser cut parts first and measuring the thickness of the 5 smallest parts. I have found that the tolerance for the acrylic is pretty bad. Edit the bowden.f3d file and create one to match the measured gap.

After you have assembled the case cover the inside with silicone sealant to keep out any moisture. You can add a spot of glue as you assemble the case to help keep things together. Make sure you use a glue that isn't quick-set and allows time for you to finish the assembly.

Print with your favourite thermoplastic | http://e3d-online.com/All-Filament

Refer to Assembly_Photos.zip for guidance when building the Spool Case. Dry assemble before gluing together.

I have exported Fusion 360 .F3D files for each component so you can edit sketches and modify things to your own design.

Hardware Required.

6 x M4 30mm Hex Stand-Offs.
4 x M4 20mm Hex Stand-Offs.
12 x M4 40mm Button Head Hex Screws.
14 x M4 12mm Button Head Hex Screws.
6 x M4 Square nuts.

1 x M8 75mm Bolt.
2 x M8 Washers.
1 x M8 Hex Half nut (Optional, used with thinner spools).

2 x 608ZZ Bearings.

1 x Threaded Bowden Coupling.
1 x Short Length of PTFE.
1 x O-Ring 10mm x 2mm (optional).

1 x 1/8 BSP Tap.

1 x Acrylic Glue.
1 x Silicone Sealant.

Alternatively there is the SpoolWorks Scaffold Soluble Support Spool Carrier which can be used with most other spools.

title: Prusa I3 MK2(s) alternative nozzle fan & cooling design

description.text:
PROTOTYPE working

Alterative fan-nozzle and cooling design for the Prusa I3 MK2(s) with an 40mm axial fan. The new 40mm fan has about the same air-pressure as the original 50mm blower but about 4 times more air-flow. The double sided fan duct provides more cooling for the printed part. I added an holder for a 9mm endoscope-camera too.

This thing is just "in build", so no guarantee if it is working. I accept no liability for damages !

This is a remix of following things found here in thingiverse :
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2065461
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2003467
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2096668
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1958083
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1846705

The thing consists of 7 parts. Mandatory is part 0 and part 1. Optional is part 4 (camera holder) part 5 (x-carriage bearing block) and part 6 (fan-cap). Part 2 and 3 are slightly modified, but you can use the original parts from Prusa too if you use the original bearings.

Be carefull : The extruder-body from the MK2s didn't fit to this thing, The PINDA probe holder is too big. But you can "downgrade" to the old MK2 extruder-holder or this thing : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1958083

If you use part 5 (x-carriage bearing block), it's mandatory to upgrade the z-axis-top too : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1846705

Update :
Modified part 3 to fit igus RJZM-01-08 or RJM-01-08 (16mm). If you use the original LM8UU bearing, igus RJZM-02-08 or RJ4JP-01-08 (15mm), take the original x-carriage from Prusa or use this one : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2438025

Update :
Fixed some errors in the mesh and fix an old bug in the x-carriage that the belt is rubbing on the idler. Added optional 6th and 7th part.

Update :
Updated part 6. Old glued part is rattling the extruder if it is not 100% centered. The new screwed part avoid this problem.

Update :
Just replaced the extruder on my printer. Seems to work well. You can read the whole thread here in the Prusa forum : http://shop.prusa3d.com/forum/improvements-f14/alternative-nozzle-cooling-t4395.html

Update :
Fixed another belt rubbing at the x-carriage (Part 3)

This holder is going great with MacBook Pro Retina Connection Lock for cables. This allow we to setup my workspace in matter of seconds.

Remember to print it using with greater values of infill then normally, because your precious laptop is hanging on it!

remixed_from.title: Customizable Miniature Burma-Shave Road Signs Redux

description.text:
While I was working on the "Customizable Miniature Burma-Shave Road Signs Redux" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2289808) recently I noticed how much the vertical arrangement of the Burma-Shave signs reminded me of a church hymn board. This, in turn, reminded me of the humorous "Highway Hymns" I'd once seen on the net. With their public safety slant matched to various highway speeds, they seemed the perfect candidates for miniature highway sign duty.

I modified the OpenSCAD script from the Burma-Shave signs remix to provide slightly larger signs with five of the six signs having three customizable text regions. The signs are a snug press-fit on the signposts and don't require adhesive. If you have a single extruder printer, pause your signs print before the text begins to print and change filament to create the contrasting text color on the signs. If you slice the signs at a layer height of 0.20mm, this pause will be between layer 18 and layer 19. Recommend that you use 20% infill on the signs and 100% infill on the signposts.

Initially, I was just going to publish this thing as a one-off, but since it was done in OpenSCAD I uploaded it to Customizer. The signs, like the Burma-Shave signs, are good, general purpose miniature signs that can be easily repurposed. They also offer the flexibility of "hymn board" or "Burma-Shave" mounting options.

OK, I've scratched my OpenSCAD sign itch for the moment, I'll go quietly...
